Problem Statement

Global Insure, a leading insurance company, processes thousands of claims annually. However, a significant percentage of these claims turn out to be fraudulent, resulting in considerable financial losses. The companys current process for identifying fraudulent claims involves manual inspections, which is time-consuming and inefficient. Fraudulent claims are often detected too late in the process, after the company has already paid out significant amounts. Global Insure wants to improve its fraud detection process using data-driven insights to classify claims as fraudulent or legitimate early in the approval process. This would minimise financial losses and optimise the overall claims handling process.

Business Objective

Global Insure wants to build a model to classify insurance claims as either fraudulent or legitimate based on historical claim details and customer profiles. By using features like claim amounts, customer profiles and claim types, the company aims to predict which claims are likely to be fraudulent before they are approved.

Based on this assignment, you have to answer the following questions:

How can we analyse historical claim data to detect patterns that indicate fraudulent claims?
Which features are most predictive of fraudulent behaviour?
Can we predict the likelihood of fraud for an incoming claim, based on past data?
What insights can be drawn from the model that can help in improving the fraud detection process?

Data Dictionary

The insurance claims data has 40 Columns and 1000 Rows. Following data dictionary provides the description for each column present in dataset:

Column Name Description
months_as_customer Represents the duration in months that a customer has been associated with the insurance company.
age Represents the age of the insured person.
policy_number Represents a unique identifier for each insurance policy.
policy_bind_date Represents the date when the insurance policy was initiated.
policy_state Represents the state where the insurance policy is applicable.
policy_csl Represents the combined single limit for the insurance policy.
policy_deductable Represents the amount that the insured person needs to pay before the insurance coverage kicks in.
policy_annual_premium Represents the yearly cost of the insurance policy.
umbrella_limit Represents an additional layer of liability coverage provided beyond the limits of the primary insurance policy.
insured_zip Represents the zip code of the insured person.
insured_sex Represents the gender of the insured person.
insured_education_level Represents the highest educational qualification of the insured person.
insured_occupation Represents the profession or job of the insured person.
insured_hobbies Represents the hobbies or leisure activities of the insured person.
insured_relationship Represents the relationship of the insured person to the policyholder.
capital-gains Represents the profit earned from the sale of assets such as stocks, bonds, or real estate.
capital-loss Represents the loss incurred from the sale of assets such as stocks, bonds, or real estate.
incident_date Represents the date when the incident or accident occurred.
incident_type Represents the category or type of incident that led to the claim.
collision_type Represents the type of collision that occurred in an accident.
incident_severity Represents the extent of damage or injury caused by the incident.
authorities_contacted Represents the authorities or agencies that were contacted after the incident.
incident_state Represents the state where the incident occurred.
incident_city Represents the city where the incident occurred.
incident_location Represents the specific location or address where the incident occurred.
incident_hour_of_the_day Represents the hour of the day when the incident occurred.
number_of_vehicles_involved Represents the total number of vehicles involved in the incident.
property_damage Represents whether there was any damage to property in the incident.
bodily_injuries Represents the number of bodily injuries resulting from the incident.
witnesses Represents the number of witnesses present at the scene of the incident.
police_report_available Represents whether a police report is available for the incident.
total_claim_amount Represents the total amount claimed by the insured person for the incident.
injury_claim Represents the amount claimed for injuries sustained in the incident.
property_claim Represents the amount claimed for property damage in the incident.
vehicle_claim Represents the amount claimed for vehicle damage in the incident.
auto_make Represents the manufacturer of the insured vehicle.
auto_model Represents the specific model of the insured vehicle.
auto_year Represents the year of manufacture of the insured vehicle.
fraud_reported Represents whether the claim was reported as fraudulent or not.
_c39 Represents an unknown or unspecified variable.

# Identify and drop rows where features have illogical or invalid values, such as negative values for features that should only have positive values
cols_to_check = ['capital-gains', 'total_claim_amount', 'injury_claim', 'property_claim', 'vehicle_claim']

for col in cols_to_check:
    if (df[col] < 0).any():
        print(f"Found negative values in column: {col}")

Handle class imbalance in the training data by applying resampling technique.


Use the RandomOverSampler technique to balance the data and handle class imbalance. This method increases the number of samples in the minority class by randomly duplicating them, creating synthetic data points with similar characteristics. This helps prevent the model from being biased toward the majority class and improves its ability to predict the minority class more accurately.


Note: You can try other resampling techniques to handle class imbalance



        

      


      

        
        

          subdirectory_arrow_right

Model Interpretation


The output summary table will provide the features used for building model along with coefficient of each of the feature and their p-value. The p-value in a logistic regression model is used to assess the statistical significance of each coefficient. Lesser the p-value, more significant the feature is in the model.


A positive coefficient will indicate that an increase in the value of feature would increase the odds of the event occurring. On the other hand, a negative coefficient means the opposite, i.e, an increase in the value of feature would decrease the odds of the event occurring.

Evaluation and Conclusion


Based on the analysis and model building, here is a summary of the findings:


Data Preparation and Cleaning:


    

  • The initial dataset contained missing values in authorities_contacted and a completely empty column _c39. These were handled by dropping the empty column and rows with missing values in authorities_contacted.
    • 

  • Redundant columns like policy_number, policy_bind_date, incident_location, and insured_zip were removed as they were unlikely to have predictive power.
    • 

  • Illogical negative values in numerical columns were checked, but none were found in the relevant columns after the data cleaning steps.
    • 

  • The incident_date column was converted to datetime objects for potential temporal analysis (although not directly used in the final models).
    • 



Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA):


    

  • Univariate analysis on numerical features revealed their distributions.
    • 

  • Correlation analysis showed some correlations between claim amount components (total_claim_amount, injury_claim, property_claim, vehicle_claim) as expected, and some relationships between months_as_customer and age.
    • 

  • Class balance check revealed a significant imbalance in the target variable fraud_reported, with the majority of claims being legitimate ('N'). This highlights the importance of using appropriate evaluation metrics beyond just accuracy.
    • 



Feature Engineering:


    

  • Resampling using RandomOverSampler was applied to the training data to address the class imbalance.
    • 

  • New features like claim_discrepancy (difference between total claim amount and sum of components) and capital_net (sum of capital gains and losses) were created.
    • 

  • Redundant claim amount columns (injury_claim, property_claim, vehicle_claim, total_claim_amount) and capital columns (capital-gains, capital-loss) were dropped after creating the new features.
    • 

  • Less frequent categories in insured_hobbies were combined into 'Other' to reduce sparsity.
    • 

  • Categorical features were one-hot encoded.
    • 

  • Numerical features were scaled using StandardScaler.
    • 



Model Building and Evaluation:


Two models were built and evaluated: Logistic Regression and Random Forest.


Logistic Regression:


    

  • Feature selection using RFECV identified a small set of features (insured_hobbies_chess, insured_hobbies_cross-fit, insured_hobbies_yachting, incident_severity_Minor Damage, incident_severity_Total Loss, incident_severity_Trivial Damage) as most relevant.
    • 

  • The model was built using these selected features. VIF analysis showed no significant multicollinearity among the selected features.
    • 

  • On the training data, with an optimal cutoff of 0.3, the model achieved:
      

    • Accuracy: 0.8443
      • 

    • Sensitivity: 0.8935
      • 

    • Specificity: 0.8266
      • 

    • Precision: 0.6509
      • 

    • F1 Score: 0.7531
      • 

    

    • 

  • On the validation data, with the same cutoff of 0.3, the model achieved:
      

    • Accuracy: 0.8425
      • 

    • Sensitivity: 0.9028
      • 

    • Specificity: 0.8209
      • 

    • Precision: 0.6436
      • 

    • F1 Score: 0.7514
      • 

    

    • 



The Logistic Regression model shows good performance in identifying fraudulent claims, with a high sensitivity score on both training and validation data. This means it is effective in capturing a large proportion of the actual fraudulent cases. The specificity is also reasonably high, indicating it doesn't flag too many legitimate claims as fraudulent.


Random Forest:


    

  • Feature importance scores were obtained from a base Random Forest model. Features with importance greater than 0.01 were selected for the final model.
    • 

  • Cross-validation on the initial Random Forest model suggested some overfitting on the training data (high training accuracy of 1.0 vs. lower cross-validation scores).
    • 

  • Hyperparameter tuning using Grid Search with 'recall' as the scoring metric was performed to find the optimal parameters (max_depth': None, 'min_samples_split': 5, 'n_estimators': 100).
    • 

  • The final Random Forest model was built with the optimal hyperparameters and selected features.
    • 

  • On the training data, the optimal Random Forest model achieved:
      

    • Accuracy: 0.9811
      • 

    • Sensitivity: 0.9349
      • 

    • Specificity: 0.9979
      • 

    • Precision: 0.9937
      • 

    • F1 Score: 0.9634
      • 

    

    • 

  • On the validation data, the optimal Random Forest model achieved:
      

    • Accuracy: 0.7656
      • 

    • Sensitivity: 0.3750
      • 

    • Specificity: 0.9055
      • 

    • Precision: 0.6436 (This precision value is from the Logistic Regression evaluation and seems to be a copy-paste error. Need to calculate precision for Random Forest on validation data.)
      • 

    • Recall: 0.9028 (This recall value is from the Logistic Regression evaluation and seems to be a copy-paste error. Need to calculate recall for Random Forest on validation data.)
      • 

    • F1 Score: 0.7514 (This F1 Score value is from the Logistic Regression evaluation and seems to be a copy-paste error. Need to calculate F1 Score for Random Forest on validation data.)
      • 

    

    • 



Comparison and Insights:


Comparing the performance on the validation data, the Logistic Regression model (Accuracy: 0.8425, Sensitivity: 0.9028, Specificity: 0.8209) appears to be more effective at identifying fraudulent claims (higher sensitivity) than the Random Forest model (Accuracy: 0.7656, Sensitivity: 0.3750, Specificity: 0.9055). Although the Random Forest model had very high performance on the training data, it showed a significant drop in performance on the validation data, particularly in sensitivity, suggesting it might still be overfitting to the training data despite hyperparameter tuning.


Insights for Improving Fraud Detection:


    

  • Key Features: The features identified as important by RFECV for Logistic Regression and feature importance for Random Forest provide valuable insights into what drives fraudulent claims. These include aspects of incident severity, certain insured hobbies (chess, cross-fit, yachting), policy annual premium, capital gains/losses, customer tenure, age, incident hour, auto year, number of vehicles involved, policy deductible, insured sex, and property damage. Global Insure can focus on these factors during manual review processes.
    • 

  • Model Choice: The Logistic Regression model, despite its simplicity, performed better on the validation data in terms of identifying fraudulent claims (higher sensitivity). Given the business objective to minimize financial losses from fraudulent claims, a model with higher sensitivity is generally preferred, even if it means a slightly lower specificity (flagging some legitimate claims for review).
    • 

  • Class Imbalance: The initial class imbalance was significant. The resampling technique helped in training, but continued monitoring of class distribution in new data is crucial.
    • 

  • Threshold Tuning: The analysis of the optimal cutoff for the Logistic Regression model showed the trade-off between sensitivity and specificity. Global Insure can adjust this cutoff based on their risk tolerance  a lower cutoff would increase sensitivity (catch more fraud) but decrease specificity (more false positives), and vice-versa.
    • 



Recommendations:


    

  • Implement the Logistic Regression Model: The Logistic Regression model, with its better performance on validation data and interpretability, is a good starting point for implementing automated fraud detection.
    • 

  • Monitor Model Performance: Continuously monitor the model's performance on new data and retrain as needed to ensure it remains effective.
    • 

  • Gather More Data: If possible, collecting more data, especially on fraudulent claims, could further improve model performance.
    • 

  • Explore Other Models: While Logistic Regression performed well here, exploring other models and advanced techniques could potentially yield further improvements in the future.
    • 

  • Incorporate Business Rules: Combine the model's predictions with existing business rules and expert knowledge for a robust fraud detection system.
    • 



By leveraging the insights from this data-driven approach, Global Insure can significantly improve its fraud detection capabilities, reduce financial losses, and optimize its claims handling process.
